## 8. Bitcoin as an Extended Phenotype of Humanity

Richard Dawkins introduced the concept of the **extended phenotype** in his 1982 book of the same name, arguing that the effects of a gene extend beyond the organism's body into the environment. [12](#user-content-fn-12) A beaver's dam is part of the beaver's extended phenotype; the intricate architecture of a termite mound is part of the termite's extended phenotype. These structures are expressions of the organism's genetic code, shaped by natural selection to serve the organism's survival and reproduction.

Bitcoin can be understood as an extended phenotype for humanity — a structure built by humans, shaped by the evolutionary pressures of economic competition and game theory, that serves the survival and flourishing of its builders. But the metaphor cuts both ways. An extended phenotype, strictly defined, is a structure that enhances the *genetic* fitness of its builders. Does Bitcoin do this? The answer is not yet clear. What is clear is that Bitcoin enhances humanity's *informational* and *economic* fitness — our ability to coordinate, transact, and maintain records across vast distances and time horizons without relying on trusted intermediaries. Whether this translates into reproductive fitness in the Darwinian sense is a question for the coming centuries.

The academic paper by Schmalzried (2025) situates this co-evolutionary process within the broader context of humanity's evolution as a "superorganism" — a collective entity whose behavior is shaped by the emergent dynamics of millions of interacting individuals. Drawing on Nate Hagens' superorganism framework and Francis Heylighen's "global brain" theory, Schmalzried argues that blockchain technology represents a new layer of coordination infrastructure for the human superorganism — a nervous system for global economic activity that operates without central control. [13](#user-content-fn-13)

Bitcoin, as a blockchain designed for unbounded scaling, is uniquely positioned to serve as this infrastructure — a global data ledger capable of recording not just financial transactions but any form of information that requires a tamper-proof, publicly verifiable record.

